  "text": "Abnormal mineral metabolism start early in course of CKD and ESRD, and is usually accompanied by profound changes in mineral metabolism that leads to clinical problems such as bone diseases, musculoskeletal symptoms and growth retardation. Recent study has found a strong association between mortality and abnormal mineral metabolism; presumably mediated by vascular calcification. [CITATION_1] The disturbances include calcium, phosphate, vitamin D, and PTH homeostasis. So, mineral metabolism outcomes are gaining importance in HD treatment. Hyperphosphatemia is one of the major factors responsible for alterations in mineral and bone metabolism in dialysis patients. [CITATION_2] In our study, the control of serum phosphorus values was adequate in 53% of patients undergoing HD, while 42% of the patients presented with hyperphosphatemia. These findings are ",
